@node features "Features"

                               Features

-There's no complex installation: just run the game and play!

-X_Lights is a "Workbench" game, so it is meant to be played on the
 Workbench screen. The game window can be resized up to a maximum of
 640 x 400 pixels, and the game is redisplayed according to the new
 window size. If the window is too small, it will be automatically
 resized to the smallest displayable size.

-As the game uses as little of the computer's ressources as possible,
 you can run other applications, games, etc. at the same time.

-X_Lights works on all Amigas with Workbench 1.3 or higher.

@endnode

@node histo "History"

                               Versions History

  What follows are the various updates that were done since the first
version of this game.

1.0: -First public release.

1.01: -Some minor changes were made to the program code.

1.02: -Many changes were made to the program code, particularly in the
       routine that generates the game window size.

1.03: -Bugfix: In some circumstances the game could crash when its window
       was resized.

1.1: -No more blitting objects! Now the game draws the lightbulbs or other
      game objects with simple OS friendly commands (it is more usable for
      systems using Amiga emulators such as MorphOS, Amithlon, etc.).
     -Some cosmetic changes were made (the buttons have been redrawn, the 
      pull-down menus were enhanced).
     -Various improvements were made to the program code.

@endnode

@node play "The game: Installation/Playing"

                             Installation

  The installation is very simple, just place 'X_Lights' where you want on
your hard drive, floppy disk, Ram Disk, etc. No other files or Libraries are
needed.

                             How to play?

  Playing 'X_Lights' is very simple: just click on a light bulb, this
will toggle all the lights on the same row and diagonally from where
you clicked (N.B.: A light is 'On' when it is in white, and 'Off' when
it is black).

  When you start the game, unless you play the @{b}Harder@{ub} game, only one
light bulb is changed, so it is easy to find which light to toggle.
But as the game level goes up, more and more lights are switched (on or
off, depending on their state) and it becomes more difficult to find out
which lights you have to change.

  If you have choosen the @{b}Harder@{ub} difficulty level, the game begins
at level 15. Obviously it is much harder to complete a level, but I
added this option in case you found the game was too simple in the easy
levels of play...

  When all the lights are 'On', the level is completed, and the game
displays a new, more difficult level.

  You can always restart the level you were on by clicking on the
@{b}Restart@{ub} button, if you think you have messed up the board and want
to restart with a new 'shuffled' board.

  Have fun!

                                 OPTIONS

 In the game window, there are 3 buttons:

 -@{b}Restart@{ub}:     Restarts the current playing level. This is handy after
               you have wrestled about half an hour on a particular
               level, you can restart with a new shuffled board.

 -@{b}About...@{ub}:    Displays the informations about the game.

 -@{b}Easy/Harder@{ub}: This is a toggle button between the 'Easy' and
               the 'Harder' game. With the harder game, you start at
               level 15.

 There is also a pull-down menu containing the following items:

 -@{b}Restart Level@{ub}: Restarts the current playing level
                 (Keyboard equivalent: Right-Amiga + "R").

 -@{b}About@{ub}:         Displays the informations about the game.

 -@{b}Quit@{ub}:          Quits the game (Right-Amiga + "Q").

@endnode

